     = Transatlantis\n| image          = Transatlantis 8.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Christian Wagner (director)|Christian Wagner]]\n| producer       = Christian Wagner\n| writer         = Christian Wagner\n| starring       = [[Daniel Olbrychski]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Thomas Mauch\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|1995|2}}\n| runtime        = 116 minutes\n| country        = Germany\n| language       = German\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Transatlantis''''' is a 1995 German [[drama film]] directed by [[Christian Wagner (director)|Christian Wagner]]. It was entered into the [[45th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1995/02_programm_1995/02_Programm_1995.html |title=Berlinale: 1995 Programme |accessdate=1 January 2012 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Daniel Olbrychski]] as Neuffer\n* [[Birgit Aurell]] as Nele\n* [[J\u00f6rg Hube]] as Brack\n* [[Malgorzata Gebel]] as Solveig\n* [[Otto Gr\u00fcnmandl]] as Rubacher\n* [[Rolf Illig]] as Dr. Hilbig\n* [[Hubert Mulzer]] as G\u00e4beles Hans\n* [[Guenter Burger]] as Branko Ristic\n* [[Michael Wogh]] as Herburger\n* [[Karl Knaup]] as Weininger (as Karl-Heinz Knaup)\n* [[Harry Meacher]] as Peary\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0114718|title=Transatlantis}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Transatlantis}}\n[[Category:1995 films]]\n[[Category:1995 drama films]]\n[[Category:German films]]\n[[Category:German drama films]]\n[[Category:German-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Christian Wagner]]\n{{1990s-Germany-film-stub}}\n{{1990s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transatlantis"}
{"title_page": "Jai Shri Ram", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Italics}} \n{{short description|Phrase meaning \"Hail Lord Rama\", often chanted in Hinduism}}\n[[File:Ram in Ayodhya.jpg|thumb|207x207px|A depiction of Ram in Ayodhya.]]\n'''''Jai Shri Ram''''' is a Hindi expression, translating to \"Glory to Lord [[Rama]]\" or \"Victory to Lord Rama\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053 |title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry |date=2019-07-10 |work=BBC News |access-date=2020-02-04 |language=en-GB}}</ref> The proclamation has been used as an informal greeting<ref>{{Cite book |last=Menon |first=Kalyani Devaki |url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/product/454038 |title=Everyday Nationalism: Women of the Hindu Right in India |date=2011-07-06 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |isbn=978-0-8122-0279-3 |page=190 |language=en |chapter=Notes |doi=10.9783/9780812202793 |jstor=j.ctt3fj1wh |chapter-url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/books/9780812202793/9780812202793.183/9780812202793.183.xml}}</ref> or as a symbol of adhering to Hindu [[faith]]<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Agrawal |first=Purushottam |date=1994 |title='Kan Kan Mein Vyape Hein Ram': The Slogan as a Metaphor of Cultural Interrogation |journal=Oxford Literary Review |volume=16 |issue=1/2 |pages=245\u2013264 |doi=10.3366/olr.1994.010 |issn=0305-1498 |jstor=44244508}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ghosh |first=Shohini |date=2000 |title=Hum Aapke Hain Koun...!: Pluralizing Pleasures of Viewership |journal=Social Scientist |volume=28 |issue=3/4 |pages=83\u201390 |doi=10.2307/3518192 |issn=0970-0293 |jstor=3518192}}</ref> or for projection of varied faith-centered emotions, by Hindus in recent past.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ramachandran |first=Tanisha |date=2014-03-01 |title=A call to multiple arms! protesting the commoditization of hindu imagery in western society |journal=Material Religion |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=54\u201375 |doi=10.2752/175183414X13909887177547 |issn=1743-2200}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |date=2019-08-20 |title=Modi's party will grow stronger in West Bengal |journal=Emerald Expert Briefings |language=en |doi=10.1108/OXAN-DB245910 |issn=2633-304X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Dasgupta |first=Amlan |date=2006 |editor-last=Bakhle |editor-first=Janaki |title=Rhythm and Rivalry |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=41 |issue=36 |pages=3861\u20133863 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4418675}}</ref> \nThe expression was used by the [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]] [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) which embraced the slogan in the late 20th century, as a tool of increasing the visibility of Hinduism in public spaces and went on to use it as a war-cry, for perpetration of communal atrocities against people of other faiths.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Jaffrelot |first=Christophe |author-link=Christophe Jaffrelot |date=July 2003 |title=Communal Riots in Gujarat: The State at Risk? |url=http://archiv.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/volltextserver/4127/1/hpsacp17.pdf |journal=Heidelberg Papers in South Asian and Comparative Politics |issue=17 |page=3 |doi=10.11588/heidok.00004127 |issn=1617-5069}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Engineer |first=Asghar Ali |date=1993 |title=Bastion of Communal Amity Crumbles |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=28 |issue=7 |pages=262\u2013264 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4399390}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Breman |first=Jan |date=1993 |title=Anti-Muslim Pogrom in Surat |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=28 |issue=16 |pages=737\u2013741 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4399608}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nIn the  late 1980's, the slogan was popularised by [[Ramanand Sagar]]'s television series ''[[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan]]'', where it was used by [[Hanuman]] and the monkey army as a war cry when they fought the demon army of [[Ravan]] in order to free [[Sita]].<ref name=\"India Today\" /> The [[Vishva Hindu Parishad]] and its [[Sangh Parivar]] allies, including the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], used it in their Ayodhya [[Ayodhya dispute|Ram Janmabhoomi movement]].<ref name=\"India Today\">{{Cite news |author=Prabash K. Dutta |title=Jai Shri Ram: A slogan that changed political contours of India |newspaper=India Today |date=13 July 2019 |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/jai-shri-ram-a-slogan-that-changed-political-contours-of-india-1568051-2019-07-13}}</ref>\n\n== Usage in violent incidents ==\nIn 1992, during riots and [[Demolition of Babri Masjid]], the same slogans were raised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/19921231-babri-masjid-demolition-when-men-in-saffron-bandanas-struck-screaming-the-name-of-ram-767472-2013-05-21|title=Babri Masjid demolition: When men in saffron bandanas struck screaming the name of Ram|first1=Ravi Shankar|last1=May 21|first2=2013 ISSUE DATE:|last2=December 31|first3=1992UPDATED:|last3=July 25|first4=2013 13:22|last4=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=D'Costa |first1=Jasmine |title=Matter of Geography |date=2017 |publisher=Mosaic Press |isbn=978-1-77161-247-0 |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=TLRJDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT41&dq=Jai%20Shri%20Ram&pg=PT41#v=onepage&q=Jai%20Shri%20Ram&f=false |accessdate=11 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, before his [[Tabrez Ansari lynching|lynching, Tabrez Ansari]] was forced by the mob to chant religious slogans \"Jai Shree Ram\" and \"Jai Hanuman\".<ref name=\"BBC chant\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053|title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry|date=July 10, 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2020, in an [[Gargi College molestations|incident of mass molestation]] and sexual harassment at [[Gargi College]], the [[Communist Party of India|CPI's]] women association alleged that the perpetrators were chanting the slogan of \"Jay Shree Ram\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/india/they-shouted-jai-shri-slogans-cpis-womens-association-on-thugs-involved-in-gargi-college-mass-molestation-case|title='They shouted Jai Shri Slogans': CPI's women's association on thugs involved in Gargi College 'mass molestation' case|website=Free Press Journal}}</ref>\n\nThe chant was heard again later the same month as Hindutva-inspired rioters torched Muslim properties and houses during the [[North East Delhi riots]].<ref name=\"Delhi Riots\">{{cite news |title=Delhi Riots: Mosque Set on Fire in Ashok Nagar, Hanuman Flag Placed on Minaret |url=https://thewire.in/communalism/delhi-violence-mosque-set-on-fire-in-ashok-vihar-hanuman-flag-placed-on-top |accessdate=26 February 2020 |work=The Wire |date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ground Report: In Riot City, Hindutva Mobs Rage With Impunity as Police Watch in Silence|url=https://thewire.in/communalism/delhi-riots-jai-shri-ram-hindutva-bjp|date=25 February 2020|accessdate=26 February 2020|website=The Wire}}</ref> At least 20 people were killed in over three days of riots. Wounded residents fleeing the area described being beaten by mobs chanting the slogan, and being stopped multiple times by Hindus demanding they pull down their pants to show whether or not they were circumcised. <ref>{{cite news|title=Communal Violence Over India's Citizenship Law Leaves 20 Dead Amid Trump's Visit|url=https://time.com/5790831/india-hindu-muslim-clashes-trump-modi/|date=26 February 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|website=Time}}</ref> In one instance, an 85-year-old woman was burnt alive.<ref name=TIME/><ref>\nAarefa Johari, [https://scroll.in/article/954422/an-85-year-old-woman-was-burnt-to-death-in-her-home-in-delhis-gamri-extension An 85-year-old woman was burnt to death in her home in Delhi\u2019s Gamri extension], Scroll.in, 26 February 2020.\n</ref> The rioters were reported to have kept chanting \"Jai Shri Ram\" while beating their victims.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/02/25/world/asia/ap-as-trump-india-protests.html Death Toll Rises to 24 From Delhi Riots During Trump Trip], The New York Times, 25 February 2020.</ref> The police were also found to join in the chant while siding with the Hindu mobs.<ref>Kaushal Shroff, [https://caravanmagazine.in/conflict/delhi-violence-cops-shouted-jai-shri-ram-with-armed-hindu-mob-charged-at-muslims Delhi violence: Cops shouted \"Jai Shri Ram\" with armed Hindu mob, charged at Muslims], The Caravan, 25 February 2020.</ref> The Muslims were told ''Hindustan me rehna hoga, Jai Shri Ram kehna hoga'' (\"if you want to stay in India, you will have to chant Jai Shri Ram\").<ref>Kaushal Shroff, [https://caravanmagazine.in/conflict/delhi-violence-cops-shouted-jai-shri-ram-with-armed-hindu-mob-charged-at-muslims Delhi violence: Cops shouted \u201cJai Shri Ram\u201d with armed Hindu mob, charged at Muslims], The Caravan, 25 February 2020.</ref> Indian journalist [[Rana Ayyub]], writing in ''[[TIME]]'', commented that the slogan had become a \"racist dog whistle\" against Muslims.<ref name=TIME>\nRana Ayyub, [https://time.com/5791759/narendra-modi-india-delhi-riots-violence-muslim/ Narendra Modi Looks the Other Way as New Delhi Burns], ''TIME'', 28 February 2020.\n</ref>\n\n== Fake cases alleging usage of ''Jai Shri Ram'' ==\n{{undue weight section|date=March 2020}}\nMultiple cases have been reported where people have alleged the usage of Jai Shri Ram during an altercation or a fight which have turned out to be fake.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://thelogicalindian.com/story-feed/awareness/jai-shri-ram-false-cases/|title=False Cases Of Harassment In The Name Of 'Jai Shri Ram' Multiply|last=Sen|first=Sumanti|date=2019-07-29|website=thelogicalindian.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Karimnagar|Karimnagar]], Telangana, a man alleged that he was beaten by BJP and RSS mob for not chanting Jai Shree Ram. However, the Commissioner of  Police after investigation clarified that the incident was not communal and that the man was trashed for harassing a teenage girl. <ref>https://thelogicalindian.com/news/muslim-youth-attack/</ref> In [[Aurangabad]], a man alleged that he was beaten up by four men and forced to chant Jai Shri Ram. However, a day after filing a complaint, he admitted that he had fabricated the story in a bid to raise his stature among his community members, and teach a lesson to people who dare to challenge people from his community.<ref>https://www.indiatoday.in/crime/story/maharashtra-man-beaten-refusing-chant-jai-shri-ram-1571412-2019-07-19</ref>\n\nStudents of a Madarsa in Unnao alleged that they were beaten while playing cricket and were forced to say Jai Shri Ram. But an investigation revealed that it was a dispute between two sides over playing cricket. An imam in Bhagpat alleged that he was thrashed for refusing to chant Jai Shri Ram. Police investigations launched into the matter revealed that it was a petty brawl with some men.<ref>https://www.dnaindia.com/india/photo-gallery-up-police-deny-madrassa-students-in-unnao-were-forced-to-chant-jai-shri-ram-says-it-was-a-cricket-dispute-2771502</ref> <ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/youths-in-up-beaten-up-for-refusing-to-chant-jai-shri-ram/articleshow/70201200.cms</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Vishva Hindu Parishad]]\n[[Category:Sangh Parivar]]\n[[Category:Ayodhya dispute]]\n[[Category:Violence against Muslims]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Italics}} \n{{short description|Phrase meaning \"Hail Lord Rama\", often chanted in Hinduism}}\n[[File:Ram in Ayodhya.jpg|thumb|207x207px|A depiction of Ram in Ayodhya.]]\n'''''Jai Shri Ram''''' is a Hindi expression, translating to \"Glory to Lord [[Rama]]\" or \"Victory to Lord Rama\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053 |title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry |date=2019-07-10 |work=BBC News |access-date=2020-02-04 |language=en-GB}}</ref> The proclamation has been used as an informal greeting<ref>{{Cite book |last=Menon |first=Kalyani Devaki |url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/product/454038 |title=Everyday Nationalism: Women of the Hindu Right in India |date=2011-07-06 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |isbn=978-0-8122-0279-3 |page=190 |language=en |chapter=Notes |doi=10.9783/9780812202793 |jstor=j.ctt3fj1wh |chapter-url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/books/9780812202793/9780812202793.183/9780812202793.183.xml}}</ref> or as a symbol of adhering to Hindu [[faith]]<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Agrawal |first=Purushottam |date=1994 |title='Kan Kan Mein Vyape Hein Ram': The Slogan as a Metaphor of Cultural Interrogation |journal=Oxford Literary Review |volume=16 |issue=1/2 |pages=245\u2013264 |doi=10.3366/olr.1994.010 |issn=0305-1498 |jstor=44244508}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ghosh |first=Shohini |date=2000 |title=Hum Aapke Hain Koun...!: Pluralizing Pleasures of Viewership |journal=Social Scientist |volume=28 |issue=3/4 |pages=83\u201390 |doi=10.2307/3518192 |issn=0970-0293 |jstor=3518192}}</ref> or for projection of varied faith-centered emotions, by Hindus in recent past.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ramachandran |first=Tanisha |date=2014-03-01 |title=A call to multiple arms! protesting the commoditization of hindu imagery in western society |journal=Material Religion |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=54\u201375 |doi=10.2752/175183414X13909887177547 |issn=1743-2200}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |date=2019-08-20 |title=Modi's party will grow stronger in West Bengal |journal=Emerald Expert Briefings |language=en |doi=10.1108/OXAN-DB245910 |issn=2633-304X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Dasgupta |first=Amlan |date=2006 |editor-last=Bakhle |editor-first=Janaki |title=Rhythm and Rivalry |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=41 |issue=36 |pages=3861\u20133863 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4418675}}</ref> \nThe expression was used by the [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]] [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) which embraced the slogan in the late 20th century, as a tool of increasing the visibility of Hinduism in public spaces and went on to use it as a war-cry, for perpetration of communal atrocities against people of other faiths.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Jaffrelot |first=Christophe |author-link=Christophe Jaffrelot |date=July 2003 |title=Communal Riots in Gujarat: The State at Risk? |url=http://archiv.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/volltextserver/4127/1/hpsacp17.pdf |journal=Heidelberg Papers in South Asian and Comparative Politics |issue=17 |page=3 |doi=10.11588/heidok.00004127 |issn=1617-5069}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Engineer |first=Asghar Ali |date=1993 |title=Bastion of Communal Amity Crumbles |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=28 |issue=7 |pages=262\u2013264 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4399390}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Breman |first=Jan |date=1993 |title=Anti-Muslim Pogrom in Surat |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=28 |issue=16 |pages=737\u2013741 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4399608}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nIn the  late 1980's, the slogan was popularised by [[Ramanand Sagar]]'s television series ''[[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan]]'', where it was used by [[Hanuman]] and the monkey army as a war cry when they fought the demon army of [[Ravan]] in order to free [[Sita]].<ref name=\"India Today\" /> The [[Vishva Hindu Parishad]] and its [[Sangh Parivar]] allies, including the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], used it in their Ayodhya [[Ayodhya dispute|Ram Janmabhoomi movement]].<ref name=\"India Today\">{{Cite news |author=Prabash K. Dutta |title=Jai Shri Ram: A slogan that changed political contours of India |newspaper=India Today |date=13 July 2019 |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/jai-shri-ram-a-slogan-that-changed-political-contours-of-india-1568051-2019-07-13}}</ref>\n\n== Usage in violent incidents ==\nIn 1992, during riots and [[Demolition of Babri Masjid]], the same slogans were raised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/19921231-babri-masjid-demolition-when-men-in-saffron-bandanas-struck-screaming-the-name-of-ram-767472-2013-05-21|title=Babri Masjid demolition: When men in saffron bandanas struck screaming the name of Ram|first1=Ravi Shankar|last1=May 21|first2=2013 ISSUE DATE:|last2=December 31|first3=1992UPDATED:|last3=July 25|first4=2013 13:22|last4=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=D'Costa |first1=Jasmine |title=Matter of Geography |date=2017 |publisher=Mosaic Press |isbn=978-1-77161-247-0 |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=TLRJDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT41&dq=Jai%20Shri%20Ram&pg=PT41#v=onepage&q=Jai%20Shri%20Ram&f=false |accessdate=11 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, before his [[Tabrez Ansari lynching|lynching, Tabrez Ansari]] was forced by the mob to chant religious slogans \"Jai Shree Ram\" and \"Jai Hanuman\".<ref name=\"BBC chant\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053|title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry|date=July 10, 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2020, in an [[Gargi College molestations|incident of mass molestation]] and sexual harassment at [[Gargi College]], the [[Communist Party of India|CPI's]] women association alleged that the perpetrators were chanting the slogan of \"Jay Shree Ram\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/india/they-shouted-jai-shri-slogans-cpis-womens-association-on-thugs-involved-in-gargi-college-mass-molestation-case|title='They shouted Jai Shri Slogans': CPI's women's association on thugs involved in Gargi College 'mass molestation' case|website=Free Press Journal}}</ref>\n\nThe chant was heard again later the same month as Hindutva-inspired rioters torched Muslim properties and houses during the [[North East Delhi riots]].<ref name=\"Delhi Riots\">{{cite news |title=Delhi Riots: Mosque Set on Fire in Ashok Nagar, Hanuman Flag Placed on Minaret |url=https://thewire.in/communalism/delhi-violence-mosque-set-on-fire-in-ashok-vihar-hanuman-flag-placed-on-top |accessdate=26 February 2020 |work=The Wire |date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ground Report: In Riot City, Hindutva Mobs Rage With Impunity as Police Watch in Silence|url=https://thewire.in/communalism/delhi-riots-jai-shri-ram-hindutva-bjp|date=25 February 2020|accessdate=26 February 2020|website=The Wire}}</ref> At least 20 people were killed in over three days of riots. Wounded residents fleeing the area described being beaten by mobs chanting the slogan, and being stopped multiple times by Hindus demanding they pull down their pants to show whether or not they were circumcised. <ref>{{cite news|title=Communal Violence Over India's Citizenship Law Leaves 20 Dead Amid Trump's Visit|url=https://time.com/5790831/india-hindu-muslim-clashes-trump-modi/|date=26 February 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|website=Time}}</ref> In one instance, an 85-year-old woman was burnt alive.<ref name=TIME/><ref>\nAarefa Johari, [https://scroll.in/article/954422/an-85-year-old-woman-was-burnt-to-death-in-her-home-in-delhis-gamri-extension An 85-year-old woman was burnt to death in her home in Delhi\u2019s Gamri extension], Scroll.in, 26 February 2020.\n</ref> The rioters were reported to have kept chanting \"Jai Shri Ram\" while beating their victims.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/02/25/world/asia/ap-as-trump-india-protests.html Death Toll Rises to 24 From Delhi Riots During Trump Trip], The New York Times, 25 February 2020.</ref> The police were also found to join in the chant while siding with the Hindu mobs.<ref>Kaushal Shroff, [https://caravanmagazine.in/conflict/delhi-violence-cops-shouted-jai-shri-ram-with-armed-hindu-mob-charged-at-muslims Delhi violence: Cops shouted \"Jai Shri Ram\" with armed Hindu mob, charged at Muslims], The Caravan, 25 February 2020.</ref> The Muslims were told ''Hindustan me rehna hoga, Jai Shri Ram kehna hoga'' (\"if you want to stay in India, you will have to chant Jai Shri Ram\").<ref>Kaushal Shroff, [https://caravanmagazine.in/conflict/delhi-violence-cops-shouted-jai-shri-ram-with-armed-hindu-mob-charged-at-muslims Delhi violence: Cops shouted \u201cJai Shri Ram\u201d with armed Hindu mob, charged at Muslims], The Caravan, 25 February 2020.</ref> Indian journalist [[Rana Ayyub]], writing in ''[[TIME]]'', commented that the slogan had become a \"racist dog whistle\" against Muslims.<ref name=TIME>\nRana Ayyub, [https://time.com/5791759/narendra-modi-india-delhi-riots-violence-muslim/ Narendra Modi Looks the Other Way as New Delhi Burns], ''TIME'', 28 February 2020.\n</ref>\n\n== Fake cases alleging usage of ''Jai Shri Ram'' ==\n{{undue weight section|date=March 2020}}\nMultiple cases have been reported where people have alleged the usage of Jai Shri Ram during an altercation or a fight which have turned out to be fake.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://thelogicalindian.com/story-feed/awareness/jai-shri-ram-false-cases/|title=False Cases Of Harassment In The Name Of 'Jai Shri Ram' Multiply|last=Sen|first=Sumanti|date=2019-07-29|website=thelogicalindian.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Karimnagar|Karimnagar]], Telangana, a man alleged that he was beaten by BJP and RSS mob for not chanting Jai Shree Ram. However, the Commissioner of  Police after investigation clarified that the incident was not communal and that the man was trashed for harassing a teenage girl. <ref>https://thelogicalindian.com/news/muslim-youth-attack/</ref> In [[Aurangabad]], a man alleged that he was beaten up by four men and forced to chant Jai Shri Ram. However, a day after filing a complaint, he admitted that he had fabricated the story in a bid to raise his stature among his community members, and teach a lesson to people who dare to challenge people from his community.<ref>https://www.indiatoday.in/crime/story/maharashtra-man-beaten-refusing-chant-jai-shri-ram-1571412-2019-07-19</ref>\n\nStudents of a Madarsa in Unnao alleged that they were beaten while playing cricket and were forced to say Jai Shri Ram. But an investigation revealed that it was a dispute between two sides over playing cricket. An imam in Bhagpat alleged that he was thrashed for refusing to chant Jai Shri Ram. Police investigations launched into the matter revealed that it was a petty brawl with some men.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/photo-gallery-up-police-deny-madrassa-students-in-unnao-were-forced-to-chant-jai-shri-ram-says-it-was-a-cricket-dispute-2771502|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/youths-in-up-beaten-up-for-refusing-to-chant-jai-shri-ram/articleshow/70201200.cms|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Vishva Hindu Parishad]]\n[[Category:Sangh Parivar]]\n[[Category:Ayodhya dispute]]\n[[Category:Violence against Muslims]]\n", "name_user": "Abhishek Pujari", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFake cases alleging usage of ''Jai Shri Ram''", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jai_Shri_Ram"}
{"title_page": "George Feigley", "text_new": "{{About|the sex cult leader|the psychedelian religion|Neo-American Church}}\n[[File:George_Feigley.jpg|thumb|right|George Feigley]] \n'''George Feigley''' (June 23, 1940 \u2013 April 13, 2009) was an American church leader. He has been described as a sex [[cult]] leader.{{r|ABC|CNN|CharlestonGazette}} Feigley served over 32 years in prison for sex crimes against children, from 1975 to 2008.{{r|ABC}}\n\nIn 1971, Feigley founded an organization he called the Neo American Church (not be confused with the more notable and unrelated [[Neo-American Church]], a [[psychedelia]]n religion founded by [[Arthur Kleps]] in the mid 1960s) and the associated Neo American School. The church and school were located in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]].\n\n{{Reduced pull quote |1=left |2=We hold that the changes called creation and procreation are divine and that human sexuality is to humans the most available expression of that function of divinity... Sexual activity is the greatest act a human can do. |3=Neo American Church Manifesto |4=described by Scott Portzline{{r|CNN}}}}\nChurch doctrine emphasized the transcendent or mystical power of [[orgasm]].{{r|ABC|NYTimes}} According to police reports, it also advocated the use of children for sexual gratification.{{r|ABC}} While leading the cult, Feigley authored several publications under the [[pseudonym]] G.G. Stoctay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ebay.com/itm/THE-ZODIACAL-CALENDAR-GG-Stoctay-NEO-AMERICAN-CHURCH-SEX-CULT-SIGNED-ED-/122717215158|title=THE ZODIACAL CALENDAR GG Stoctay NEO-AMERICAN CHURCH, SEX CULT, SIGNED & #ED  {{!}} eBay|website=eBay|language=en|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> These included a book entitled ''The Sale of Lillian'', which described the [[Child sexual abuse|sexual abuse]] of a 10-year-old girl, and contained graphic illustrations of such abuse.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/?clipping_id=31159520&fcfToken=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJmcmVlLXZpZXctaWQiOjg5NzgyODg5LCJpYXQiOjE1NTY3Njk4MzcsImV4cCI6MTU1Njg1NjIzN30.ygbJIAgPv2DSVdqQoNuZ2w46p-AylYWyanR5DOTpUO4|title=Cast of figures in sewer escape cult|last=|first=|date=1983-08-06|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref>\n\nThe [[charisma]]tic{{r|ABC|HarrisburgPatriotNews}} Feigley, who called himself \"The Light of the World\",{{r|CNN|HarrisburgPatriotNews|PennLive (Harrisburg Rapist)}} gathered a small group of followers, mostly women, into his church.{{r|NYTimes|PennLive (Harrisburg Rapist)}} As of 1983, the group, which at one point had numbered over twenty persons,{{r|PennLive (Harrisburg Rapist)}} included about ten adults, one or two of whom were men (five children of group members were then living in foster homes where they had been placed by the state).{{r|NYTimes}}\n\n==Imprisonment, escape, and re-capture==\nFeigley led the church in freedom for only about five years, as he was arrested in 1975 on multiple counts of statutory rape, indecent assault, and corrupting the morals of minors. He was found guilty of statutory rape of two teen-age girls and was sentenced to 10 years to 20 years in prison.{{r|NYTimes}} His wife was found guilty of corrupting the morals of minors.\n\n{{Reduced pull quote |1=right |2=I require total devotion to my desires. You may not have a will nor desire of your own which do not project my wishes. I expect this complete commitment from my wives, my concubines and my children... Make yourselves my delight... May my peace abide with you. |3=George Feigly |4=Letter from prison{{r|PennLive (Harrisburg Rapist)}}}}\nNotwithstanding his imprisonment, some of Feigley's followers remained loyal, roaming to follow him as he was moved from prison to prison or when he was a fugitive.{{r|NYTimes}}\n\nIn 1976, Feigley scaled a prison wall at [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Rockview|SCI- Rockview]] and fled to [[West Virginia]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Leader Of Cult Is Arrested |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/30593581/feigley_recaptured_in_sneedville/ |accessdate=14 Apr 2019 |publisher=The Daily News |date=19 Feb 1979 |location=Huntingdon, Pennsylvania, U.S.A.}}</ref> While he was on the lam he hid at a farm near [[Thornton, West Virginia]], which he and his followers referred to as the \"Aaron Farm\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/?spot=18453696|title=Farm In W. Va. Once Used As Hideaway|last=Flaherty|first=Mary Pat|date=7 August 1983|work=The Pittsburgh Press|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.prisoners.com:80/heavens.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100518143931/http://www.prisoners.com:80/heavens.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-05-18|title=Views of the Prisons /81215/|date=2010-05-18|access-date=2018-03-19}}</ref> He was apprehended in 1978, but escaped from the [[Taylor County, West Virginia|Taylor County]] Jail in [[Grafton, West Virginia|Grafton]] less than a month later while awaiting extradition back to Pennsylvania.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26040960/george_feigley_escapes_from_jail_after/|title=Search for rapist|last=|first=|date=18 October 1978|work=Evening Herald of Shenandoah-Ashland-Mahanoy City|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref> He was assisted in this escape by fellow prisoner James Lee Gilbert, who joined the cult after engineering the escape.<ref name=\":1\" /> After his second escape he was free for two months before he was recaptured, hiding on another farm near [[Sneedville, Tennessee|Sneedville]], [[Tennessee]].{{r|ABC}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26041289/george_feigley_recaptured_in_tennessee/|title=Sneedville Cult Leader Charged In Prison Escape|last=|first=|date=22 February 1979|work=The Tennessean|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, plans for Feigley to escape from [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Graterford|SCI- Graterford]] by [[helicopter]] were uncovered. In response Feigley was transferred to Western Penitentiary.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHis women followers visited him regularly at the State Correctional Institution at [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Huntingdon|Huntingdon, Pennsylvania]].{{r|NYTimes}} The organization continued to operate; a 1983 raid on Feigley's home found young children playing with sex toys and boxes of child pornography. Feigley's wife and others pleaded guilty to corruption of minors and were sentenced to prison.{{r|ABC}}\n\nIn 1983, James Lee Gilbert and another of Feigley's followers, Laura Seligman, died in circumstances that led authorities to believe they were intending to break Feigley out of prison.<ref name=\":1\" /> (They drowned in a sewer line close to [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Pittsburgh|Western Penitentiary]] where Feigley was then held.){{r|ABC}}\n\nIn 1994, while still in prison, Feigley was convicted of instructing his wife and another man over a prison phone to have sex with a 14-year-old girl. Feigley was found guilty of conspiracy to commit involuntary deviate sexual intercourse and sentenced.  Because of problems with the search warrants, Feigley's wife and the girl's mother were able to plead guilty and receive probation.{{r|ABC}}\n\n== Prisoner activism ==\nIn 1996, while imprisoned, Feigley co-founded the [[Prisoner support|prisoners' advocacy]] website and [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]] corporation [https://web.archive.org/web/20090508191210/http://www.prisoners.com/ www.prisoners.com], along with his wife Sandra.<ref name=\":0\" /> He contributed to the website to the extent possible while he was in prison. Www.prisoners.com purported to be \"The Voice of the Imprisoned\" and criticized the [[Pennsylvania Department of Corrections]] for alleged [[Prisoner abuse|abuses]]. It also provided information useful to prisoners and their loved ones.\n\nThe website also featured biographies of and works of art by prisoners, and health essays by Feigley under the pseudonym \"Professor Stoctay\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prisoners.com/fiction.html#fiction|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100721191141/http://www.prisoners.com/fiction.html#fiction|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-07-21|title=Prisoner Authors /81209/|date=2010-07-21|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref> However in addition to this advocacy for prisoners, Prisoners.com also published some of Feigley's rationalizations for his crimes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/story?id=5575131&page=1|title=Child Sex 'Cult' Leader Set to Go Free|last=News|first=A. B. C.|date=2008-08-14|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> As of April 2019, the website is defunct.\n\n==Release==\nFeigley became eligible for [[parole]] in 1990, but parole was denied then and at each subsequent annual review.{{r|PennLive (Harrisburg Rapist)}} Having served the full time for all his convictions, Feigley was released from prison on August 15, 2008, to some consternation.{{r|ABC}}{{r|CNN}}{{r|Turley}} His convictions were not covered under Pennsylvania's [[Megan's Law]]s (his 1976 conviction preceded Megan's Law, and conspiracy to commit involuntary deviate sexual intercourse \u2014 his 1994 charge \u2014 isn't covered under the law), so he was not required to register as a sex offender,{{r|ABC}} nor was he on parole as he had served his sentences in full.\n\nHis return home was met with a crowd of protestors.{{r|PennLive (A Small Crowd)}} A neighbor circulated a petition to prevent Feigley's return to his home.{{r|PennLive (Single Mom Fights)}}\n\n== Death ==\nFeigley, who left prison in poor health,{{r|PennLive (Harrisburg Rapist)}} died on April 13, 2009.{{r|Tributes}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n*[[List of prison escapes]]\n*[[List of helicopter prison escapes]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100721194057/http://www.prisoners.com/homepg2.html#main www.prisoners.com] (archive)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=ABC>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/story?id=5575131 |title=Child Sex 'Cult' Leader Freed from Prison |first1=Lindsay |last1=Goldwerd |first2=Teri |last2=Whitcraft |date=August 14, 2008 |work=ABC News |accessdate=June 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=NYTimes>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/12/04/us/inmate-said-to-lead-cult-mixing-sex-and-religion.html |title=Inmate Said to Lead Cult Mixing Sex and Religion |author=Associated Press |date=December 4, 1983 |work=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=June 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=CNN>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/08/15/cult.leader.release/ |title=Terms of Sex Cult Leader's Release Anger Community |date=August 15, 2008 |work=CNN |accessdate=June 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=CharlestonGazette>{{cite news |title=Sex Cult Leader Lived in West Virginia |first=Gary |last=Harki |date=August 22, 2008 |work=Charleston Gazette |location=West Virginia }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Turley>{{cite web |last=Turley |first=Jonathan |author-link=Jonathan Turley |title=Community Outraged by Unrestricted Release of Religious Pedaphilic Leader |date=August 16, 2008 |work=Jonathan Turley |url=https://jonathanturley.org/2008/08/16/community-outraged-by-unrestricted-release-of-religious-pedaphilic-leader/ |accessdate=June 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=HarrisburgPatriotNews>{{cite news |title=For Feigley, Prison Was New Beginning |first=Carrie |last=Cassidy  |date=August 10, 2008 |work=Harrisburg [Pennsylvania] Patriot-News }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"PennLive (A Small Crowd)\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2008/08/a_small_crowd_protests_as_conv.html |title=A Small Crowd Protests as Convicted Rapist George Feigley Arrives at His House |first=Michael |last=Fernandez |date=August 15, 2008 |work=Penn Live |accessdate=June 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"PennLive (Harrisburg Rapist)\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2008/08/convicted_rapist_to_leave_pris.html |title=Harrisburg Rapist to Be Released from Prison |author=<!-- No author; staff by-line. --> |date=August 9, 2008 |work=Penn Live |accessdate=June 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Tributes>{{cite web |url=http://www.tributes.com/obituary/show/George-E.-Feigley-85827174 |title=George E. Feigley |work=Tributes.com |accessdate=June 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"PennLive (Single Mom Fights)\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2008/08/single_mom_fights_sexcult_lead.html |title=Single Mom Fights Sex-Cult Leader's Return to Neighborhood |author=<!-- No author; staff by-line. --> |date=August 12, 2008 |work=Penn Live |accessdate=June 17, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feigley, George}}\n[[Category:People from Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American escapees]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of child sexual abuse]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of indecent assault]]\n[[Category:Religious figures convicted of child sexual abuse]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of rape]]\n[[Category:American prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:20th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the sex cult leader|the psychedelian religion|Neo-American Church}}\n[[File:George_Feigley.jpg|thumb|right|George Feigley]] \n'''George Feigley''' (June 23, 1940 \u2013 April 13, 2009) was an American church leader. He has been described as a sex [[cult]] leader.{{r|ABC|CNN|CharlestonGazette}} Feigley served over 32 years in prison for sex crimes against children, from 1975 to 2008.{{r|ABC}}\n\nIn 1971, Feigley founded an organization he called the Neo American Church (not be confused with the more notable and unrelated [[Neo-American Church]], a [[psychedelia]]n religion founded by [[Arthur Kleps]] in the mid 1960s) and the associated Neo American School. The church and school were located in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]].\n\n{{Reduced pull quote |1=left |2=We hold that the changes called creation and procreation are divine and that human sexuality is to humans the most available expression of that function of divinity... Sexual activity is the greatest act a human can do. |3=Neo American Church Manifesto |4=described by Scott Portzline{{r|CNN}}}}\nChurch doctrine emphasized the transcendent or mystical power of [[orgasm]].{{r|ABC|NYTimes}} According to police reports, it also advocated the use of children for sexual gratification.{{r|ABC}} While leading the cult, Feigley authored several publications under the [[pseudonym]] G.G. Stoctay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ebay.com/itm/THE-ZODIACAL-CALENDAR-GG-Stoctay-NEO-AMERICAN-CHURCH-SEX-CULT-SIGNED-ED-/122717215158|title=THE ZODIACAL CALENDAR GG Stoctay NEO-AMERICAN CHURCH, SEX CULT, SIGNED & #ED  {{!}} eBay|website=eBay|language=en|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> These included a book entitled ''The Sale of Lillian'', which described the [[Child sexual abuse|sexual abuse]] of a 10-year-old girl, and contained graphic illustrations of such abuse.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/?clipping_id=31159520&fcfToken=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJmcmVlLXZpZXctaWQiOjg5NzgyODg5LCJpYXQiOjE1NTY3Njk4MzcsImV4cCI6MTU1Njg1NjIzN30.ygbJIAgPv2DSVdqQoNuZ2w46p-AylYWyanR5DOTpUO4|title=Cast of figures in sewer escape cult|last=|first=|date=1983-08-06|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref>\n\nThe [[charisma]]tic{{r|ABC|HarrisburgPatriotNews}} Feigley, who called himself \"The Light of the World\",{{r|CNN|HarrisburgPatriotNews|PennLive (Harrisburg Rapist)}} gathered a small group of followers, mostly women, into his church.{{r|NYTimes|PennLive (Harrisburg Rapist)}} As of 1983, the group, which at one point had numbered over twenty persons,{{r|PennLive (Harrisburg Rapist)}} included about ten adults, one or two of whom were men (five children of group members were then living in foster homes where they had been placed by the state).{{r|NYTimes}}\n\n==Imprisonment, escape, and re-capture==\nFeigley led the church in freedom for only about five years, as he was arrested in 1975 on multiple counts of statutory rape, indecent assault, and corrupting the morals of minors. He was found guilty of statutory rape of two teen-age girls and was sentenced to 10 years to 20 years in prison.{{r|NYTimes}} His wife was found guilty of corrupting the morals of minors.\n\n{{Reduced pull quote |1=right |2=I require total devotion to my desires. You may not have a will nor desire of your own which do not project my wishes. I expect this complete commitment from my wives, my concubines and my children... Make yourselves my delight... May my peace abide with you. |3=George Feigly |4=Letter from prison{{r|PennLive (Harrisburg Rapist)}}}}\nNotwithstanding his imprisonment, some of Feigley's followers remained loyal, roaming to follow him as he was moved from prison to prison or when he was a fugitive.{{r|NYTimes}}\n\nIn 1976, Feigley scaled a prison wall at [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Rockview|SCI- Rockview]] and fled to [[West Virginia]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Leader Of Cult Is Arrested |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/30593581/feigley_recaptured_in_sneedville/ |accessdate=14 Apr 2019 |publisher=The Daily News |date=19 Feb 1979 |location=Huntingdon, Pennsylvania, U.S.A.}}</ref> While he was on the lam he hid at a farm near [[Thornton, West Virginia]], which he and his followers referred to as the \"Aaron Farm\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/?spot=18453696|title=Farm In W. Va. Once Used As Hideaway|last=Flaherty|first=Mary Pat|date=7 August 1983|work=The Pittsburgh Press|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.prisoners.com:80/heavens.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100518143931/http://www.prisoners.com:80/heavens.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-05-18|title=Views of the Prisons /81215/|date=2010-05-18|access-date=2018-03-19}}</ref> He was apprehended in 1978, but escaped from the [[Taylor County, West Virginia|Taylor County]] Jail in [[Grafton, West Virginia|Grafton]] less than a month later while awaiting extradition back to Pennsylvania.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26040960/george_feigley_escapes_from_jail_after/|title=Search for rapist|last=|first=|date=18 October 1978|work=Evening Herald of Shenandoah-Ashland-Mahanoy City|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref> He was assisted in this escape by fellow prisoner James Lee Gilbert, who joined the cult after engineering the escape.<ref name=\":1\" /> After his second escape he was free for two months before he was recaptured, hiding on another farm near [[Sneedville, Tennessee|Sneedville]], [[Tennessee]].{{r|ABC}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26041289/george_feigley_recaptured_in_tennessee/|title=Sneedville Cult Leader Charged In Prison Escape|last=|first=|date=22 February 1979|work=The Tennesseean|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, plans for Feigley to escape from [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Graterford|SCI- Graterford]] by [[helicopter]] were uncovered. In response Feigley was transferred to Western Penitentiary.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHis women followers visited him regularly at the State Correctional Institution at [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Huntingdon|Huntingdon, Pennsylvania]].{{r|NYTimes}} The organization continued to operate; a 1983 raid on Feigley's home found young children playing with sex toys and boxes of child pornography. Feigley's wife and others pleaded guilty to corruption of minors and were sentenced to prison.{{r|ABC}}\n\nIn 1983, James Lee Gilbert and another of Feigley's followers, Laura Seligman, died in circumstances that led authorities to believe they were intending to break Feigley out of prison.<ref name=\":1\" /> (They drowned in a sewer line close to [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Pittsburgh|Western Penitentiary]] where Feigley was then held.){{r|ABC}}\n\nIn 1994, while still in prison, Feigley was convicted of instructing his wife and another man over a prison phone to have sex with a 14-year-old girl. Feigley was found guilty of conspiracy to commit involuntary deviate sexual intercourse and sentenced.  Because of problems with the search warrants, Feigley's wife and the girl's mother were able to plead guilty and receive probation.{{r|ABC}}\n\n== Prisoner activism ==\nIn 1996, while imprisoned, Feigley co-founded the [[Prisoner support|prisoners' advocacy]] website and [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]] corporation [https://web.archive.org/web/20090508191210/http://www.prisoners.com/ www.prisoners.com], along with his wife Sandra.<ref name=\":0\" /> He contributed to the website to the extent possible while he was in prison. Www.prisoners.com purported to be \"The Voice of the Imprisoned\" and criticized the [[Pennsylvania Department of Corrections]] for alleged [[Prisoner abuse|abuses]]. It also provided information useful to prisoners and their loved ones.\n\nThe website also featured biographies of and works of art by prisoners, and health essays by Feigley under the pseudonym \"Professor Stoctay\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prisoners.com/fiction.html#fiction|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100721191141/http://www.prisoners.com/fiction.html#fiction|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-07-21|title=Prisoner Authors /81209/|date=2010-07-21|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref> However in addition to this advocacy for prisoners, Prisoners.com also published some of Feigley's rationalizations for his crimes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/story?id=5575131&page=1|title=Child Sex 'Cult' Leader Set to Go Free|last=News|first=A. B. C.|date=2008-08-14|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> As of April 2019, the website is defunct.\n\n==Release==\nFeigley became eligible for [[parole]] in 1990, but parole was denied then and at each subsequent annual review.{{r|PennLive (Harrisburg Rapist)}} Having served the full time for all his convictions, Feigley was released from prison on August 15, 2008, to some consternation.{{r|ABC}}{{r|CNN}}{{r|Turley}} His convictions were not covered under Pennsylvania's [[Megan's Law]]s (his 1976 conviction preceded Megan's Law, and conspiracy to commit involuntary deviate sexual intercourse \u2014 his 1994 charge \u2014 isn't covered under the law), so he was not required to register as a sex offender,{{r|ABC}} nor was he on parole as he had served his sentences in full.\n\nHis return home was met with a crowd of protestors.{{r|PennLive (A Small Crowd)}} A neighbor circulated a petition to prevent Feigley's return to his home.{{r|PennLive (Single Mom Fights)}}\n\n== Death ==\nFeigley, who left prison in poor health,{{r|PennLive (Harrisburg Rapist)}} died on April 13, 2009.{{r|Tributes}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n*[[List of prison escapes]]\n*[[List of helicopter prison escapes]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100721194057/http://www.prisoners.com/homepg2.html#main www.prisoners.com] (archive)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=ABC>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/story?id=5575131 |title=Child Sex 'Cult' Leader Freed from Prison |first1=Lindsay |last1=Goldwerd |first2=Teri |last2=Whitcraft |date=August 14, 2008 |work=ABC News |accessdate=June 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=NYTimes>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/12/04/us/inmate-said-to-lead-cult-mixing-sex-and-religion.html |title=Inmate Said to Lead Cult Mixing Sex and Religion |author=Associated Press |date=December 4, 1983 |work=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=June 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=CNN>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/08/15/cult.leader.release/ |title=Terms of Sex Cult Leader's Release Anger Community |date=August 15, 2008 |work=CNN |accessdate=June 16, 2016}}</